Here&#39;s how `equals` affects other code:

    public Card deal() {
        Random rand = new Random();
        Card randomCard;

        randomCard = m_cards.get(rand.nextInt(m_cards.size()));
        m_cards.remove(randomCard);

        return randomCard;
    }

`m_cards.remove(randomCard)`  think how this method is going to know which card to remove from the collection? Exactly, it calls `equals` with the parameter and every item in the collection!

You have to decide: is a seven of hearts really _equal_ to a seven of clubs? I don&#39;t think so. They might have the same rank, but for them to be considired equal, I&#39;d expect them to have the same rank _and_ the same suit.

The canonical implementation of this method is (more or less):

    public boolean remove(final Object o) {
        final Iterator&lt;E&gt; it = iterator();
        while (it.hasNext()) {
            if (Objects.equals(o, it.next())) {
                it.remove();
                return true;
            }
        }
        return false;
    }

PS Random instances should be reused, not recreated with `new` every time you need them. If you recreate, you are not getting good random values and might even end up with the same number several times in a row. To reuse, create it once in the constructor or store it in a `static final` field.

